          "body": "Verses 19-24 present Elisha's first two independent prophetic acts, and they are deliberately paired as positive and negative demonstrations of the same authority. The healing of Jericho's spring (2:19-22) is an act of creation-restoration: the water that brings death and unfruitfulness (*shakhol*, miscarriage or barrenness) is transformed by the prophetic word into water that sustains life. The mechanism is instructive — salt in a new bowl, thrown into the spring — but the salt does not heal; God heals ('Thus says the Lord, I have purified these waters,' 2:21). The new bowl may signify a new beginning; the salt may evoke the covenant-salt of Leviticus 2:13. Either way, the text insists that the word of Elisha accomplishes what it says, and the result is permanent: 'to this day' (2:22). The judgment at Bethel (2:23-24) has troubled commentators across centuries. The mockers are described as *ne'arim* (2:23) and *yeladim* (2:24) — young men or lads, not necessarily small children. Their taunt 'Go up, you baldhead' is likely a contemptuous dismissal of both Elisha's person and the translation event itself — 'go up' echoes Elijah's going up (2:1, 11), and 'baldhead' may be a derogatory term for a prophet's shaved head or a mark of social contempt. The curse in the name of the Lord and the bear-mauling that follows is divine judgment on the mockery of God's anointed, at the most spiritually compromised city in the northern kingdom. Together, the two signs establish what Peter Davids notes of prophetic authority in the New Testament epistolary context as well: the apostolic (here prophetic) word both heals and judges, and neither function can be separated from the authority of the One who speaks through the prophet."
